The '''Sagaiguninini''' (‘people of the lake’)<ref name="three">{{cite web |url=http://www.wordways.com/articles/web/ASURVEYOFAMERICANINDIANLOGOLOGY.pdf |title=A SURVEY OF AMERICAN INDIAN LOGOLOGY |work=Susan Thorp}}</ref> were allegedly a sub-nation of the Algonquin group.<ref name="zero">{{cite book | last =Hessel | first = Peter | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =The AIgonkin Tribe, The Algonkins of the Ottawa Valley: An Historical Outline | publisher = Kichesippi Books | series = | volume = | edition = | year = 1987 | location = | pages = | language = | url = http://www.thealgonquinway.ca/publications/TheAlgonkinTribe_4_00.pdf | doi = | id = | isbn =0-921082-01-0 | mr = | zbl = | jfm = }}</ref> In 1630-1640, the group lived south-west of the Ottawa river and may have been unrelated to the rest, "as nearly all the other bands are on or northeast of the Ottawa River". <ref name="two">{{cite web |url=http://www.canadiangenealogy.net/indians/algonkin_indians.htm |title=Algonkin Indians of Canada |work=Canadian Genealogy}}</ref> They lived east of Georgian Bay and what is now know to locals as "The Big Three" lakes in Ontario ([[Lake Rosseau]], [[Lake Muskoka]], [[Lake Joseph]]). Very little is known about this group today, however the [[Algonquin people|Algonquin]] word "sagaigun" means lake<ref name="zero"/> and their name is still part of the local culture and language. The town of [[Seguin, Ontario]] and the steam ship [[RMS Segwun]] are good example of names that have carried into the modern age.
